section.section:
An incorporated society, order, or supreme lodge without capital stock is deemed to be a fraternal benefit society if it:
is conducted solely for the benefit of its members and their beneficiaries;
is not conducted for profit;
is operated on a lodge system with ritualistic form of work;
has a representative form of government; and
provides for benefits to be paid in accordance with this subtitle.

text.section:
A society is deemed to have a representative form of government if:
the society provides in its laws for a supreme legislative or governing body composed of:
election of delegates may be accomplished by mail;
the elected representatives of the society:
at least once every 4 years:
each insured member is eligible for election to act or serve as a delegate to the meeting;
the society has a board of directors that:
the officers of the society are elected by the supreme legislative or governing body or by the board of directors; and
the members, officers, representatives, or delegates of the society may not vote by proxy; or
the society provides in its laws for a supreme legislative or governing body composed of:
election of the board may be accomplished by mail;
the term of an elected board member may not exceed 4 years;
the individuals elected to the board:
vacancies on the board between elections are filled as prescribed by the laws of the society;
an individual filling the unexpired term of an elected board member is considered to be an elected member; and
the board meets at least quarterly to conduct the business of the society.
